<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-016-940  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 016 940.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Business  Dec 11 1989 v15 n24 p58(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Globalization forces changes in trade barriers of the past.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Berkman, Barbara N.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>International trade will change considerably during the 1990suntil the economy is integrated, or 'globalized.' Trade barrierswill break down in the 1990s, beginning with the creation of asingle European market in 1992, and continuing with the bilateraltrade agreement between the US and Canada and economic reform inEastern Europe and the USSR.andP;  The electronic equipment industry isexpected to increase to over two and a half trillion by 2000;Japan will increase its market share slightly, from 32 to 36percent, while the US share will decline from 29 to 24 percent.andO;Market access, especially between the US and Japan, will remain apoint of controversy, although some US manufacturers recently havebeen successful in the Japanese market.andP;  An integrated marketcreates the need for a delicate balance because inflation,oversupply and debt could wreak havoc on the world economy.andP;  Jobcreation and low inflation are vital.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     International TradeEconomics of ComputingManufacturingCommerceWorld Market.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Worldwide electronic equipment production. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>